## Overview
This project focuses on analyzing restaurant data using **PostgreSQL** to uncover business insights related to sales performance, customer behavior, and menu popularity.  
The analysis helps restaurant owners and managers make **data-driven decisions** to improve revenue and operational efficiency.

## Problem Statement
Restaurants generate large amounts of transactional data, but without proper analysis it is difficult to:
- Identify top-selling menu items
- Understand peak business hours
- Analyze customer ordering patterns
- Track overall revenue performance

This project solves these problems using **SQL queries in PostgreSQL**.

## Objectives
- Analyze restaurant sales and order data
- Identify best and worst performing menu items
- Understand peak order timings
- Generate insights for business optimization

## Database & Tools
- **Database:** PostgreSQL  
- **Language:** SQL  
- **Tool Used:** pgAdmin / psql  
- **Environment:** Relational Database System (RDBMS)

## Database Schema
The database consists of the following tables:

### 1. customers
| Column | Description |
|------|-------------|
| customer_id | Unique customer ID |
| customer_name | Name of the customer |

### 2. menu
| Column | Description |
|------|-------------|
| item_id | Unique menu item ID |
| item_name | Name of the dish |
| price | Price of the item |

### 3. orders
| Column | Description |
|------|-------------|
| order_id | Unique order ID |
| customer_id | Customer placing the order |
| order_date | Date of order |

### 4. order_details
| Column | Description |
|------|-------------|
| order_id | Order reference |
| item_id | Menu item ordered |
| quantity | Quantity ordered |

## Data Analysis Performed
The following analyses were performed using SQL queries:

- Total revenue generated
- Top-selling and least-selling menu items
- Number of orders per customer
- Daily and monthly sales trends
- Average order value
- Peak ordering hours and days

